    <p class="font-bold mb-2">Start 1-on-1 Lessons with See Guru</p>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">See Guru combines budget pricing with professional materials and progress tracking. Lessons start from $5/hour with native and near-native tutors.</p>
    <a href="https://see.guru/?aff=SG-SUAG151" class="inline-block bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700 text-white font-semibold px-6 py-3 rounded-lg transition">Try See Guru</a>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-4">
    <div>
      <h3 class="font-bold mb-2">How many 1-on-1 lessons do I need to improve my English?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Most learners need 20-30 lessons before noticing significant improvement in speaking confidence. For measurable progress toward fluency, plan for 50-100 lessons over 6-12 months. The key is consistency rather than lesson volume. One well-prepared lesson per week beats five rushed sessions.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h3 class="font-bold mb-2">Are community tutors as good as certified teachers?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Community tutors often provide better conversation practice because they focus on natural dialogue rather than formal curriculum. Certified teachers excel at structured learning goals like exam preparation or grammar mastery. For pure conversation fluency, community tutors frequently deliver better value.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h3 class="font-bold mb-2">Should I stick with one tutor or rotate between multiple?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Commit to one tutor for at least 5-10 lessons to build rapport and allow them to understand your learning style. After that, you can either continue with your established tutor or try others to find different perspectives. Some learners maintain one primary tutor for curriculum and rotate conversation tutors for variety.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h3 class="font-bold mb-2">What is the best length for 1-on-1 lessons?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">25-30 minute lessons work best for most learners. This length maintains focus while allowing enough time for meaningful practice. Advanced learners who can sustain concentration may benefit from 50-60 minute sessions. Shorter micro-sessions of 15 minutes suit beginners who fatigue quickly.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h3 class="font-bold mb-2">How do I prepare for 1-on-1 lessons to maximize value?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Before each lesson, write down specific questions, topics you want to practice, and areas where you struggled during the past week. Share these notes with your tutor at the start of the session. Come ready to speak for at least 50% of the lesson time. Follow up by reviewing lesson recordings or notes within 24 hours.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

